text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Expansion: Learning tones for non-native Mandarin speakers%0a:Author: david_h%0a:Original: [[Articles.ToneSystemsComparingEnglishAndMandarin|ToneSystemsComparingEnglishAndMandarin]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.BenP|BenP]]%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 27.02.2021 - 09:33%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210512-121317-437520#%0a* [-12.05.2021 - 05:13-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210512-121317-437520#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aStudies have shown that one of the greatest difficulties of English speakers learning Mandarin is the tonal system. Since English does not have a tonal system that dictates lexical differences, intentionally producing pitch changes and contours where they are needed is often inconsistent and error-prone.%0a%0aOne linguist Chao Yuan-ren helped people to better understand how Mandarin tones should sound like by assigning each tone to a musical scale equivalent. This helps solve the problem of non-native Mandarin speakers from using incorrect pitch and/or contours when speaking Mandarin.%0a%0aAn interesting observation mentioned in the study is that some tones are harder for native speakers of non-tonal languages to learn. The easiest to learn was T1 (high level), then T4 (falling stressing), followed by T2 (rising) and T3 (falling and rising) respectively.%0a%0aSource:%0a%0aShi, Hui, "A Method of Teaching English Speaking Learners to Produce Mandarin-Chinese Tones" (2018).%0aGraduate Theses, Dissertations, and Problem Reports. 6633.%0ahttps://researchrepository.wvu.edu/etd/6633%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a#foxbegin 210512-000939-369750#%0a!!Backup interface%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a#foxend 210512-000939-369750#%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
