diff:1614447198:1614447198:=1,48d0%0a%3c :Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a%3c :Expansion: Learning tones for non-native Mandarin speakers%0a%3c :Author: david_h%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.ToneSystemsComparingEnglishAndMandarin|ToneSystemsComparingEnglishAndMandarin]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.BenP|BenP]]%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 27.02.2021 - 09:33%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Studies have shown that one of the greatest difficulties of English speakers learning Mandarin is the tonal system. Since English does not have a tonal system that dictates lexical differences, intentionally producing pitch changes and contours where they are needed is often inconsistent and error-prone.%0a%3c %0a%3c One linguist Chao Yuan-ren helped people to better understand how Mandarin tones should sound like by assigning each tone to a musical scale equivalent. This helps solve the problem of non-native Mandarin speakers from using incorrect pitch and/or contours when speaking Mandarin.%0a%3c %0a%3c An interesting observation mentioned in the study is that some tones are harder for native speakers of non-tonal languages to learn. The easiest to learn was T1 (high level), then T4 (falling stressing), followed by T2 (rising) and T3 (falling and rising) respectively.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c %0a%3c Shi, Hui, "A Method of Teaching English Speaking Learners to Produce Mandarin-Chinese Tones" (2018).%0a%3c Graduate Theses, Dissertations, and Problem Reports. 6633.%0a%3c https://researchrepository.wvu.edu/etd/6633%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Ca